{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}} {{Use Australian English|date=November 2011}} {{Infobox poker player |name=Mark Vos |nickname=pokerbok |image=Mark_Vos.jpg |caption=Mark Vos at the [[2008 World Series of Poker]] |hometown=Cape Town, South Africa |birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|10|20}} |wsop bracelet count=1 |wsop money finishes=9 |wsop main event best finish rank=80th |wsop main event best finish year=2008 |wpt titles= |wpt final tables= |wpt money finishes= |ept titles=''None'' |ept final tables=''None'' |ept money finishes=1 |updated=2009-09-20 }}
'''Mark Vos''' (born 20 October 1983), also known as 'pokerbok', is a professional [[poker]] player from [[Australia]]. Vos was born in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]], and attended Waldorf High School in [[Constantia, Cape Town|Constantia]]. He excelled at [[International Mathematical Olympiad|mathematics olympiads]] while in high school, and represented his province in the interprovincial olympiad. Vos permanently deferred his [[Actuary|actuarial studies]] at [[Macquarie University]], to play poker full-time. Starting out online with limit [[Texas Holdem|hold'em]] in mid-2004, Vos soon turned his attention to no-limit games, and in short time, earned a reputation as being one of the world's top online poker players, such that he can often be found playing in the most expensive [[cash game]]s and tournaments online. When not travelling the world playing poker, Vos plans to divide his time between Australia and South Africa.<ref name="fulltilt">[http://www.fulltiltpoker.com/markVos.php FullTilt.net Player profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711150649/http://www.fulltiltpoker.com/markVos.php |date=11 July 2007 }}</ref> In January 2006, Vos finished 8th in the main event of the [[Crown Australian Poker Championship]], winning [[A$]]83,600. As of May 2006, Vos represents the [[Full Tilt Poker]] online poker cardroom as a friend of Full Tilt Poker. His name is reflected in red on Full Tilt tables.
In July 2006, Vos won Event 6 at the [[2006 World Series of Poker]] ([[World Series of Poker|WSOP]]), the [[2006 World Series of Poker Results#Event 6: .242.2C000 No Limit Hold .27em|$2000 no limit hold 'em event]]. Outlasting a field of 1,919 players, Vos entered heads up action with [[Nam Le (poker player)|Nam Le]] an almost 3:1 chip underdog. On the final hand, Vos raised to $90,000 preflop and Le made the call. The flop came {{cards|Qs|8s|3h}} and Le check-called a $150,000 bet by Vos. The turn was the {{cards|2d}} and Le check-called for $250,000. The river brought the {{cards|Qd}} to which Le checked and Vos moved all in. Le, suspecting a bluff, made the call with {{cards|6c|6d}}, but Vos turned over {{cards|Qc|10c}} for trips and the win, collecting $803,274 and the gold [[WSOP bracelet|bracelet]], becoming one of the youngest WSOP bracelet winners in history. After his victory, Vos said, "[Winning] does not really change things. I mean, it helps. But I still plan to play poker, then [in five years] I'll relax, settle down and decide what I want to do with the rest of my life." <ref name="pokerpages">[http://www.pokerpages.com/tournament/result13601.htm PokerPages.com Tournament Report] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514031148/http://www.pokerpages.com/tournament/result13601.htm |date=14 May 2007 }}</ref> Vos cashed four times at the 2008 World Series of Poker including finishing in 80th place out of 6,844 entries in the $10,000 buy-in Main Event, earning $77,200.
As of 2009, his total live tournament winnings exceed $1,200,000. His 9 cashes at the WSOP account for $977,728 of those winnings.<ref>[http://www.worldseriesofpoker.com/players/index.asp?sort=cashearned&pagenum=2 World Series of Poker Earnings] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090809184243/http://www.worldseriesofpoker.com/players/index.asp?sort=cashearned&pagenum=2 |date=9 August 2009 }}, worldseriesofpoker.com</ref>
